initial fixes: 

change tesseract.exe to portable then use relative path

expand subtitle window or even the whole video and let tesseract segment everything



next problem is no subtitles being generated (one letter at best)
 
this has to do with the MAX_HASH_DIFFERENCE_FOR_SAME_SUBTITLE value which is the one responsible for this problem. 
lowering the value fixes it 

i also tried a hash size of 128 (note that the NO_SUBTITLE_FRAME_HASH also has to be modified to equate in size) 
but i think that will be detrimental since the animation of the second line will have a big effect on the hashes 
generated (too much detail captured)
LOWER HASH SIZE


this is a dilemma since a lower hash size would be like squinting at the Japanese characters which would result in 
the first scanned subtitle appearing in its timestamp but also in place of the succeeding subtitle

BUT A HIGHER HASH SIZE WOULD CREATE DUPLICATES WHENEVER THE SECOND LINE OF THE SUBTITLES ARE ANIMATED


FIX division by zero error when using video.stream.get(cv2.CAP_PROP_FPS)
i think a crude fix would be to store its value in a variable and when it is zero, assume it to be 60                                

code snippet:
initial_fps = video.stream.get(cv2.CAP_PROP_FPS)
frame_number_in_millis = 1000 * frame_number / initial_fps


